**Title:** Comparative Analysis of Deep Learning Models for Electrocardiogram (ECG) Signal Processing and Arrhythmia Detection

**Description:** This dataset contains a comprehensive analysis of various deep learning models applied to ECG signal processing and arrhythmia detection. **Data Characteristics:**

* **Dataset Size:** 10,000 ECG recordings with corresponding annotations for AF and other arrhythmias
* **Signal Features:** Time-domain and frequency-domain features extracted from the ECG signals, including heart rate variability (HRV), P-wave duration, and morphologic variability

	+ CNNs with convolutional and pooling layers
	+ RNNs with recurrent and attention mechanisms
	+ Transformers with self-attention and feed-forward networks
* **Evaluation Metrics:** Accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, F1-score, and area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC-ROC) used to evaluate model performance

**Findings:**

* The study found that deep learning models can achieve high accuracy in detecting AF and other cardiac arrhythmias from ECG recordings
* CNNs and RNNs showed comparable performance in terms of AUC-ROC, while transformers demonstrated improved performance on certain datasets
* The best-performing model was a transformer-based architecture with self-attention and feed-forward networks, achieving an AUC-ROC of 0.95

**Conclusion:** This study demonstrates the effectiveness of deep learning models in processing ECG signals and detecting cardiac arrhythmias.
